{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491368"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:44:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:44:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"923"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/923"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.1,0.09,0.16,0.59]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"923"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92447"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/923"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"923"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75764"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"435"},{"type":"tags","id":"8883"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28379"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31636"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31637"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92447"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old man presents with a two day history of blindness in the right eye. His medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes. On examination both eyes appear normal, his blood pressure is 170/95 mmHg and pulse 92/min and regular.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFundoscopy shows the following (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the loss of vision?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Retinal detachment","Central retinal artery occlusion","Diabetes mellitus","Hypertension","Central retinal vein occlusion"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERetinal vein occlusion (RVO) is a common cause of vision loss in older patients. There are two types of\u00a0\u00a0RVO, branch or central. \u003Cstrong\u003ECentral retinal vein occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E (CRVO) is further divided into non-ischaemic or ischaemic. Non-ischaemic CRVO is the most common, accounting for 70% of cases; the characteristic symptoms include mild visual changes with no pupillary defect. Whereas ischaemic CRVO characteristically has moderate to severe vision loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe primary risk factor for CRVO is age, with 90% of patients older than 50 years old. Other primary risk factors include hypertension, open-angle glaucoma, diabetes mellitus and hyperlipidaemia. As with any thrombotic event, the three main factors that contribute are venous stasis, endothelial damage and hypercoagulability. Patients with CRVO will describe sudden, painless, blurry or distorted vision in one eye. Fundoscopic examination of CRVO is classically described as \u2018blood and thunder\u2019 due to the extensive haemorrhages throughout the retina. This patient\u2019s fundoscopy shows widespread intra-retinal haemorrhages: the superficial ones follow the curve of the nerve fibre bundles near the surface of the retina, whilst the deeper ones are the \u0027dots and blots\u0027 that extend vertically alongside the connecting neurones from the basal rods to the superficial ganglion cells. The white patches are areas of nerve fibre infarction (formerly descriptively called \u0027cotton-wool spots\u0027).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment of CRVO includes both medical and surgical options. Medically, intravitreal injections of anti-VEGF have been shown to reduce new blood vessel growth and swelling; while surgical options include laser photocoagulation and chorioretinal venous anastomosis, but the latter is done in few centres.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Central retinal vein occlusion is an important acute of rapid loss of vision in older patients."],"references":["Blair K, Czyz CN. Central Retinal Vein Occlusion.\u00a0\u00a0StatPearls. Treasure Island (FL)2020.","Karia N. Retinal vein occlusion: pathophysiology and treatment options. Clin Ophthal 2010; 4:809-16."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75764"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"923"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"200"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/200"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/99e6d9d8-b437-44ee-90b0-32d480b225f2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/99e6d9d8-b437-44ee-90b0-32d480b225f2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":556,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75764"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-17T20:11:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-17T20:12:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"923"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92447"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":